							<h1 id="dev-I">I. Introduction to Development Environments</h1>
							<p>An IDE can improve the productivity of software developers thanks to fast setup and standardization across tools.</p>
							<p>Without an IDE, developers spend time deciding what tools to use for various tasks, configuring the tools and learning how to use them. Many or even all of the necessary dev-test tools are included in one integrated development environment.</p>
							<p>IDEs are also designed with all their tools under one user interface. An IDE can standardize the development process by organizing the necessary features for software development in the UI.</p>
							
							<p>Some examples of popular IDEs and their respective languages include:</p>

							<ul>
								<li>Eclipse - Java</li>
								<li>PyCharm - Python</li>
								<li>Visual Studio Code - Multiple</li>
								<li>intelliJ IDEA - Java</li>
								<li>NetBeans - Java</li>
								<li>Xcode - Multiple (primarily Swift)</li>
							</ul>

							<p>We will discuss why these IDEs can make your life a lot easier in the IDE section</p>

							<hr>

							<h1 id="dev-II">II. Text Editors</h1>

							<p>If you’re working on a coding project, you’ll want to save your code files to your computer. </p>

							<p>Using programs like Microsoft Word or Notepad is not recommended for writing code. Text editors provide a great environment to write and edit code.</p>

							<p>Some examples of great text editors are:</p>

							<ul>
								<li>Sublime Text</li>
								<li>Atom</li>
								<li>Notepad++</li>
								<li>Vim</li>
								<li>Emacs</li>
							</ul>

							<p>These are just a few of many text editors available for free. Keep in mind, that text editors do not compile code for you, and that you may have to compile your code through the command line.</p>

							<p>For help with running your programs on the command line, refer to the command line section</p>

							<hr>

							<h1 id="dev-III">III. IDEs</h1>

							<p>As mentioned earlier in the introduction section, IDEs are great for many things.</p>

							<p>They provide quick set up and compile time for programs. Everything is readily available in a single interface</p>

							<p>For examples of great IDEs and their corresponding languages, refer to the introduction section</p>

